                    <msContents>
                        <summary>Fol. 1a. The Proverbs of Solomon. Same division as in Manuscript no.1. The text had many faults, which have been corrected by another hand. The text shows numerous variant readings, as compared with the Asmara edition of the Ethiopic Bible -- 36a. The Book of Ecclesiastes -- 48b. The Wisdom of Solomon -- 59a. The Wisdom of Jesus son of Sirach
                        </summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">
                            <locus from="1r">Fols 1r and following</locus>
                            <title>Proverbs of Solomon</title>                            
                        </msItem>
                        <msItem xml:id="ms_i2">
                            <locus from="36r">Fols 36r and following</locus>
                            <title>Book of Ecclesiastes</title>                            
                        </msItem>
                        <msItem xml:id="ms_i3">
                            <locus from="48v">Fols 48v and following</locus>
                            <title>Wisdom of Solomon</title>                            
                        </msItem>
                        <msItem xml:id="ms_i4">
                            <locus from="59r">Fols 59r and following</locus>
                            <title>Wisdom of Jesus son of Sirach</title>                            
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="Codex">
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><material key="parchment"/></support>
                                <extent><measure unit="leaf">119</measure> <dimensions type="outer" unit="mm">
                                    <height>250  </height>
                                    <width>190</width>                                        
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <condition key="deficient">The margins of the leaves are brown and worn out. The first and the last leaf are worm eaten.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            
                            <layoutDesc><layout columns="2" writtenLines="24"/></layoutDesc>
                            
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">The writing is big and calligraphic. The book-headings are decorated with pen-and-ink drawings. The writing and the drawings have a striking likeness with the Manuscript Orient.650 of the British Museum (see facsimile in W. Wright's Catalogue of the Ethiopic Manuscripts in the British Museum, London 1887), which is dated from the reign of Zar'a Ya'kob (1434-68). Paleographically, the manuscript seems to belong approximately to the same period.</handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <list>
                                <item xml:id="a1"><desc>On the verso of the fly-leaf at the beginning of the volume, there is an eulogy from another, less skilled hand, which has become partly illegible, but which shows clearly that the manuscript was written for a Falasha or belonged at some time to a Falasha.</desc></item>
                                <item xml:id="e1"><desc type="findingAid">For the purpose of public or private reading, the book is divided into sections to be read each on its day, between the 26th Maskaram andthe 15th Teqemt. The dates are written with red ink at the top of the leaves on which the respective sections begin</desc></item>
                            </list>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b1">bound in wood-covers with leather back</decoNote>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
